		"body": "## Summary\r\n\r\nThis pull request fixes an issue in `showMissingMasterKeyMessage()` in `packages/lib/services/e2ee/utils.ts`.\r\n\r\nThe function filters out disabled master keys from `notLoadedMasterKeys` before deciding whether to show the missing master key warning. It used `Array.pop()` inside a reverse-index-based loop. Since `pop()` always removes the last element of the array, it could remove the wrong key when the disabled key was not at the end of the list.\r\n\r\nThis change replaces that logic with `splice(i, 1)` so that the disabled key at the current index is removed correctly.\r\n\r\n## Problem\r\n\r\nCurrent code:\r\n\r\n    for (let i = notLoadedMasterKeys.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\r\n        const mk = syncInfo.masterKeys.find(mk => mk.id === notLoadedMasterKeys[i]);\r\n\r\n        if (!mk) continue;\r\n        if (!masterKeyEnabled(mk)) notLoadedMasterKeys.pop();\r\n    }\r\n\r\nIn this loop, the intent is to remove the disabled key currently being inspected. However, `.pop()` removes the last array element, not the element at index `i`.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n- `notLoadedMasterKeys = [key1_disabled, key2_disabled, key3_enabled]`\r\n- When the loop reaches `key2_disabled`, `.pop()` removes `key3_enabled`\r\n- This leaves incorrect key IDs in the array during warning evaluation\r\n\r\n## What this PR changes\r\n\r\n- Replaces `notLoadedMasterKeys.pop()` with `notLoadedMasterKeys.splice(i, 1)` in `showMissingMasterKeyMessage()`\r\n- Adds a regression test covering the case where disabled keys appear before an enabled key in `notLoadedMasterKeys`\r\n\r\n## Why this fix is correct\r\n\r\nThe loop already iterates in reverse, which is a safe pattern when removing elements by index during iteration.\r\n\r\nUsing `splice(i, 1)` removes exactly the disabled key currently being processed, which matches the intended behaviour of the function.\r\n\r\n## Testing\r\n\r\n### Automated tests\r\n\r\nAdded a regression test in:\r\n\r\n`packages/lib/services/e2ee/utils.test.ts`\r\n\r\nThe test covers a case where:\r\n\r\n- Multiple keys are present\r\n- Disabled keys appear before an enabled key\r\n- Only disabled keys should be removed from the warning check\r\n\r\n### Manual verification\r\n\r\n1. Create multiple master keys.\r\n2. Mark some keys as disabled and leave at least one enabled.\r\n3. Pass those key IDs through the missing master key warning path.\r\n4. Confirm that only disabled keys are filtered out.\r\n5. Confirm that the warning still appears when an enabled unloaded key remains.\r\n6. Confirm that no warning appears when only disabled unloaded keys remain.\r\n\r\n## Impact\r\n\r\nThis change is limited to the filtering logic in a single E2EE utility function and does not introduce any public API changes.\r\n\r\n## Related issue\r\n\r\nFixes #14821",
